content.div:
Let's say you got married, were lavished with $100,000 in wedding presents -- and then filed for divorce three months later. (So, basically, let's say you're Kim Kardashian.)

The etiquette of these situations can seem so tricky sometimes. What does one do with a $7,500 vase, gifted by your closest billionaire acquaintance? We've been searching Martha Stewart's website for hours, and nothing.

127 days after splitting from Kris Humphries, though, Kardashian has finally made a move. TMZ reports that she's mailed out thank-you cards -- and also made a sizable donation to the Dream Foundation (the adult equivalent of Make a Wish), sending them a cheque for $200,000, or roughly twice the estimated value of her wedding haul.

"Kim felt that this was the most fitting way to acknowledge and pay forward your gift with the same compassion and kindness it was intended," a rep for the Dream Foundation writes in a message included in Kardashian's thank-you notes.

Her local stationery merchant is no doubt grateful for the business -- but what about all that Hermes crockery and Baccarat barware she hauled in through her registry? Us Weekly notes that a charity, the Dream Foundation included, doesn't often have much use for luxury tat. Kardashian, the magazine reports, is keeping her wedding presents -- and her ex, much like Miss Manners, does not approve.

"Kris has always felt they should return gifts to the people that spent their money on it," a source tells the magazine, adding that the NBA player does, however, approve of her charitable gesture. "Kris respects Kim for donating money and is happy she is doing that. He 100 per cent thinks that is great, but she should give the gifts back."

Apparently Humphries isn't blameless, however -- holed up in Minnesota somewhere with several editions of Emily Post. A friend of Kardashian's, Jonathan Cheban, told TMZ that he gave Humphries a $5,000 YSL gift card. He hasn't gotten it back, though -- so if Humphries is going to criticize Kardashian for how she handled the gift situation, Cheban says Humphries ought to be returning his haul, too.

It's somewhat uncertain whether the couple's pre-nup agreement is keeping them from giving back the gifts. One source familiar with the pre-nup tells Us Weekly that they're free to do what they will with all their swag; another says that "by court order, they are not supposed to do anything with the presents until the marriage is dissolved completely and they both decide how everything will end up."

The rules of etiquette, however, are more clear. As Lizzy Post, author of the most recent edition of Emily Post's Etiquette, explained to the New York Daily News: "The rule of thumb is if the marriage ends after just six months, you should return the unused gifts," she stated. "After just 72 days, the gifts must be returned to the wedding guest.”

leahc@dose.ca
